article.headline: Yao has 25 and 17, and has final defensive say
article.linkText: Yao leads Rockets past Raptors in OT
article.story: HOUSTON (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy spoke and Steve Francis listened. Yao Ming scored 27 points and had 17 rebounds, but it was a shot he missed that Steve Francis followed with a slam dunk for the game's biggest basket. Thanks to Francis' hustle, the Houston Rockets took a 90-89 overtime victory over the Toronto Raptors on Wednesday night. With the game tied at 86 in overtime, Yao maneuvered for a layup, but it rolled off the rim. Francis came out of nowhere with a dunk in one movement to give the Rockets the lead with 1:04 left. Francis said it had a lot to do with something coach Van Gundy told him. "Coach has been after me in transition to go for offensive rebounds," said Francis, who along with Cuttino Mobley had 17 points. "It wasn't that I expected Yao to miss. I have so much confidence in him, but (offensive rebounding) is something coach has kind of been on me about the last few weeks." Yao was glad for the help. "I didn't know what was happening," he said. "Then it seemed like Steve fell out of the sky, like he came from outer space or something." Van Gundy agreed. "It was a heck of a play by Steve," Van Gundy said. "Tonight, Steve was very poised. He has been playing very well and extremely hard in the last few games. When he plays with that energy, it brings a great dimension to the team." Bostjan Nochbar hit two free throws with 51 seconds to play for a 90-86 advantage in overtime as Houston won its fifth straight from Toronto. Toronto, which has played more overtimes and won more than any team in the league this season, slipped to 6-4 in overtimes when Donyell Marshall missed a driving layup at the buzzer. A 3-pointer from Chris Bosh with 33 seconds to play had closed it to 90-89. "It was a tough game to lose and they just wouldn't let us take it from them," said Jalen Rose, who had 20 points. "They play hard on this floor. They're one of the best home teams in the league and we knew it would be tough to get one here. "On the last play, (Marshall) had a good look. He had the play we wanted, but it just didn't go down." Vince Carter scored 26 points and had a season-high 13 rebounds for the Raptors, who have won only once in nine games in Houston. "It's disappointing to lose this kind of game because we battled so hard to get back in it," Carter said. "Yao is just so much bigger than all of our big guys and he really created problems for us, especially in the first half." Houston led 64-59 after three quarters, but an 8-0 run gave Toronto a 75-74 lead with 6:16 to play in regulation. A three-pointer by Marshall then put the Raptors up 82-80 with 1:43 to go, but Mobley's layup tied it with 1:27 to play. Yao blocked a shot by Marshall with 51 seconds to play. But Francis missed a 17-footer with :04 remaining and the Raptors turned the ball over with a second left in regulation. Yao took control inside early, scoring 10 points in the first six minutes of the game as the lead went back and forth. Houston led 21-20 at the end of one period. Yao scored five more points in the second quarter as Houston led by as many as six before settling for a 43-39 halftime lead. A 13-0 run in the third quarter, including six points from Yao, gave Houston its biggest lead at 60-48 with 4:29 left in the period. ^Notes:@ Houston's Jim Jackson sat out the game with lower back stiffness. In Jackson's place, Adrian Griffin got his first start of the season. ... The win assured Houston of its 23rd .500 or better record in the 37 seasons of the franchise ... It was Yao's 29th double-double of the season ... After losing to Memphis on Tuesday night, the Raptors are 7-7 in the first game of back-to-back games and 3-11 in second games ... Carter got his seventh double-double of the season with a season-high 13 rebounds.
